That's the behavior here too.
I believe the .sparseimage format has been retained because it allows TM
to use all its hard link magic for sure, when otherwise one couldn't
trust the remote server's format to support such an unusual feature.
And because it's a sparseimage, ie something you can write to without
rewriting the complete archive (I understand in fact it's a folder full
of 8Mb &quot;slice files&quot;), it will still update very fast.

The second disk appearing is the mounted volume I believe, and you can
check it's read-only and with ownerships that are not you (this way, you
can read and recuperate the files even by hand, but you can't trash
everything too easily, you have to use the window local menu if you want
for instance eliminate a file from the backup)

