Now I think I understand. You happen to have done, inadvertently, all
the steps necessary to reactivate the network-related archiving.

What happens when Time Machine starts:
1- TM checks whether the disk it ordinarily uses for backups is
mounted
2- if yes TM checks that besides the name it is indeed the *right*
disk, with the right data on it, and if yes starts updating
3- additionally, if the disk happens to be a network disk, TM will
use, or create if there is none, a sparseimage in order to avoid any
trouble with hard link support.

On step 1, as you maintained the same name for your disk whether
directly mounted onto the mac or via Airport, it went OK

On step 2, because you initially used this disk in a &quot;validated&quot; way,
ie connected directly to the mac, TM indeed had already written all
the necessary hidden files onto it previously (there are among other
dot-files like &quot;timemachinesupportedvolume&quot; or something close to
this, with specific unix permissions -system ones not yours, etc.). TM
for now only writes these files when the disk is directly connected to
the mac -but it didn't need to write them: they already were there.
So, because all these files already existed, TM started the backup
process.
Note that if you had erased your disk before plugging it to Airport,
it wouldn't even have *appeared* in the possible backup volumes in TM
control panel!

On step 3, because now TM was determined to use your disk, and it was
a network disk, and didn't contain any .sparseimage, well, TM just
created it, ignoring any other archive files already present.

Note that if you would now re-displace the disk plugging it onto your
mac, mount the .sparseimage, and move all the initial archive folder
hierarchy inside this image, this initial archive would constitute the
basis for TM to update on when back on Airport.
Still, you may not wish to do this, because of the special unix
permissions: if you want it to work, definitely it's not from the
Finder that you must move the files, rather from a terminal with
complicated sudo copy commands with a range of extra qualifiers.

(Why would you want to do this anyway? Maybe because the initial
archive is very big, and while it's created quite fast when the disk
is directly plugged on the mac, this becomes veeeerrrrryyyy slow when
via airport.
Indeed, I believe this is THE single reason why Apple removed this
capacity in extremis: so as to avoid being flooded by complaints &quot;TM
is atrocious because I left it 24 hours on my crappy 802.11.b-linked
network disk and the first backup isn't even concluded&quot;.
Now, on the contrary, once the first archive is done, the hourly
updates are almost instant: you don't add dozens of Gb every minute to
your main hard disk, and even your biggest 100 Mb new doc + new song
flies on an Airport network.)

So, if you indeed managed to have a working backup finalized via
Airport, you can continue using it without trouble. It will never be
slow from now on, you'll always be able to redisplace the disk
directly on the mac if need be (just mount the .sparseimage), and any
network interruption will be supported by TM the same way as they are
when the disk is directly connected (e. g. you can sleep the mac in
the middle of a backup, everything will restart on wakeup).

FWIW, I am using a setup that is different but close to yours (a
Network Access drive accessed via Airport), and everything is
perfectly fine.

Hervé Sainct
